## 5. Aceternity UI — Usage Rules

Aceternity UI (https://ui.aceternity.com) is the primary UI library for animations, visual effects, and interactive components. It is built on top of Tailwind CSS and Framer Motion.

### Installation

```bash
# Install dependencies
npm install framer-motion clsx tailwind-merge

# Add Aceternity component via CLI (preferred)
npx aceternity-ui add <component-name>

# Or manually copy from https://ui.aceternity.com/components into src/components/ui/aceternity/
```

### When to Use Aceternity UI

- ALWAYS use Aceternity UI for hero sections, landing page backgrounds, and marketing UI.
- ALWAYS use Aceternity UI for animated text effects, card effects, and visual flourishes.
- PREFER Aceternity UI over hand-rolling custom Framer Motion animations.
- NEVER use Aceternity UI for functional form inputs, data tables, or complex accessibility-critical components (use Radix Primitives instead).

### Component Categories & What to Use

| Use Case          | Aceternity Component                                                           |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Hero backgrounds  | `AuroraBackground`, `BackgroundBeams`, `Spotlight`, `WavyBackground`, `Vortex` |
| Hero text effects | `TextGenerateEffect`, `TypewriterEffect`, `FlipWords`, `ColourfulText`         |
| Card effects      | `3DCardEffect`, `CardHoverEffect`, `GlareCard`, `WobbleCard`, `CardSpotlight`  |
| Scroll animations | `TracingBeam`, `StickyScrollReveal`, `HeroParallax`, `MacbookScroll`           |
| Navigation        | `FloatingNavbar`, `FloatingDock`, `Sidebar`                                    |
| Loaders           | `MultiStepLoader`, `Loader`                                                    |
| Layout sections   | `BentoGrid`, `LayoutGrid`, `Timeline`                                          |
| Testimonials      | `AnimatedTestimonials`, `InfiniteMovingCards`, `CardStack`                     |
| Buttons           | `MovingBorder`, `HoverBorderGradient`                                          |
| Decorative        | `Sparkles`, `Meteors`, `ShootingStars`, `GlowingStars`                         |

### Rules for Using Aceternity Components

- ALWAYS copy Aceternity components into `src/components/ui/aceternity/`. Never import directly from an npm package (Aceternity UI is copy-paste based).
- ALWAYS keep each Aceternity component in its own file: e.g., `src/components/ui/aceternity/aurora-background.tsx`.
- ALWAYS preserve the original component's TypeScript interfaces. Extend via wrapper components, never modify the source directly.
- ALWAYS add `'use client'` to Aceternity components since they use Framer Motion and browser APIs.
- NEVER use Aceternity background/animation components as Server Components.
- ALWAYS wrap Aceternity animation components in `next/dynamic` with `ssr: false` when used inside Server Component pages, to avoid hydration issues.
- ALWAYS test Aceternity components for performance impact. Heavy canvas or WebGL components (e.g., `GithubGlobe`, `CanvasRevealEffect`) MUST be lazy-loaded with `next/dynamic`.

```typescript
// ✅ Good — lazy load heavy Aceternity components
import dynamic from 'next/dynamic'

const BackgroundBeams = dynamic(
  () => import('@/components/ui/aceternity/background-beams').then(m => ({ default: m.BackgroundBeams })),
  { ssr: false, loading: () => <div className="absolute inset-0 bg-background" /> }
)

// ✅ Good — wrapper pattern for customization
import { SparklesCore } from '@/components/ui/aceternity/sparkles'

export function HeroSparkles({ className }: { className?: string }) {
  return (
    <SparklesCore
      background="transparent"
      minSize={0.4}
      maxSize={1}
      particleDensity={1200}
      className={cn('w-full h-full', className)}
      particleColor="#FFFFFF"
    />
  )
}
```

### Aceternity + Framer Motion Rules

- ALWAYS import Framer Motion from `'framer-motion'` directly in Aceternity component files.
- NEVER use `motion` components outside of `'use client'` files.
- ALWAYS use `useReducedMotion()` from Framer Motion to respect accessibility preferences for heavy animations.
- For entrance animations, prefer `initial`, `animate`, `exit` over imperative animation controls.
- ALWAYS use `layoutId` for shared layout animations (e.g., tabs, modals).

```typescript
'use client'

import { motion, useReducedMotion } from 'framer-motion'

export function AnimatedCard({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const shouldReduceMotion = useReducedMotion()

  return (
    <motion.div
      initial={shouldReduceMotion ? false : { opacity: 0, y: 20 }}
      animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
      transition={{ duration: 0.4, ease: 'easeOut' }}
    >
      {children}
    </motion.div>
  )
}
```

