## 8. Server Actions

- ALWAYS use native Next.js Server Actions with `'use server'`.
- ALWAYS validate input with Zod `safeParse` inside every Server Action.
- NEVER use `try/catch` for expected validation errors. Return structured error objects instead.
- ALWAYS return a consistent `ActionResponse<T>` shape from every action.
- Throw ONLY for unexpected/unrecoverable errors (caught by error boundaries).
- ALWAYS use `useActionState` in client components to handle Server Action responses.
- Use Server Actions for ALL mutations. NEVER create REST endpoints when an action suffices.
- Code in `services/` MUST throw user-friendly errors that actions can surface to the UI.

```typescript
// types/actions.types.ts
export interface ActionResponse<T = unknown> {
  success: boolean;
  data?: T;
  error?: string;
  fieldErrors?: Record<string, string[]>;
}

// actions/users.actions.ts
("use server");

import { z } from "zod";
import { userService } from "@/services/users.service";
import type { ActionResponse } from "@/types/actions.types";

const createUserSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email("Invalid email address"),
  name: z.string().min(2, "Name must be at least 2 characters"),
  password: z.string().min(8, "Password must be at least 8 characters"),
});

export async function createUserAction(
  formData: FormData,
): Promise<ActionResponse<User>> {
  const parsed = createUserSchema.safeParse(Object.fromEntries(formData));

  if (!parsed.success)
    return {
      success: false,
      error: "Validation failed",
      fieldErrors: parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors,
    };

  const user = await userService.create(parsed.data);
  return { success: true, data: user };
}
```

