## 13. Error Handling

- ALWAYS implement `error.tsx` at each route segment that needs isolated error recovery.
- ALWAYS implement `global-error.tsx` at the root for unexpected top-level failures.
- ALWAYS log unexpected errors to Sentry (or equivalent) inside error boundaries.
- NEVER show raw error messages or stack traces to users in production.
- Handle errors and edge cases at the TOP of functions using guard clauses and early returns.
- Place the happy path LAST in the function for readability.
- NEVER use `else` after an early `return`. Use the if-return pattern.
- Model expected errors as structured return values (`ActionResponse`). Throw only for unexpected errors.

```typescript
// app/dashboard/error.tsx
'use client'

import { useEffect } from 'react'
import { captureException } from '@sentry/nextjs'

export default function DashboardError({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string }
  reset: () => void
}) {
  useEffect(() => { captureException(error) }, [error])

  return (
    <div role="alert">
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <button onClick={reset}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  )
}
```

